Summary¶

In this project I performed the below steps to determine the best model. Ultimately, I decided the best performing model was Model 9, which used Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) to condense the best 50 features into a single feature and it used cross validation to help balance its sensitivity and specificity. Below is an overview of the different steps I took to build the best model.

For EDA¶

  1. Use histograms to understand distribution of the data
  2. Select features using ANOVA test
  3. Select features using kendall tau rank test
  4. Select the best 50 features from the combined ANOVA and kendall tau features using the Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE) module from sklearn
  5. Use RFE to reduce total features to 10 and 25
  6. Use LDA to condense all the features into one

I was able to narrow down my selection to the 50 best features in the data set. I then used recursive feature elimination and some dimensionality reduction techniques, like Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA), to further combine and condense my feature set into less features.

Model Selection & Comparison¶

Logistic Regression¶
  1. Try with all 50 ANOVA features
  2. Try with all 50 Kendall Tau features
  3. Try with the 50 best features selected from both the ANOVA and Kenall Tau features
  4. Use RFE to reduce features to 10
  5. Use RFE to reduce features to 25
  6. Condense features with LDA and try LR with with just LDA output
  7. Compare performance between using all features and LDA features
  8. Fine tune LDA performance using different regularizations and cross validation
SVM¶
  1. Try with LDA feature set using rbf kernel
  2. See if we can improve performance using polynomial kernel (2nd and 3rd degree)
  3. Compare and contrast performance between using SVM and Logistic Regression

I selected the Logistic Regression model that uses LDA as its preprocessing and includes cross validation during training (Model 9). This was due to

  1. Performance
  2. Accuracy
  3. Computational efficiency

Although the model had slightly higher training time than the rest of the LDA Logistic Regression models (~30 seconds more), the sensitivity and specificity of the model was slightly better than the others. Hence, I believe it was worth the trade-off for a slightly higher training time.

Histogram Analysis¶

  • Most of the data falls in a very small range

It appears that the data follows a generally normal distribution across all features. Since the data is continuous and it follows a normal distribution, I can use a couple of techniques to determine the best 50 features:

  • The ANOVA test
  • Kendall Tau's test

Unfortunately, using Chi-2 would not be best for two reasons:

  1. We do not know enough about the data, and
  2. There are negative values in the dataset.

So I will stick with the Kendall tau and ANOVA tests.

Models¶

Preparing for Reporting¶

In [10]:
from collections import namedtuple

Model = namedtuple('Model', ['estimator', 'accuracy', 'features', 'alg', 'reg', 'cv'])
all_models = []
In [11]:
def add_model(estimator, accuracy: float, features: int, alg: str, reg: str = None, cv: bool = False) -> None:
    """ Creates a new Model object and adds it to the list """
    model = Model(estimator, accuracy, features, alg, reg, cv)
    all_models.append(model)

def report_results():
    columns = ["Model Number", "Accuracy", "# Features", "Algorithm", "Regularization", "Cross-Validation"]
    max_len = len(max(columns, key=lambda x: len(x)))
    header = " | ".join('{0:{width}}'.format(col, width=max_len) for col in columns)
    print(header)
    print("-" * len(header))
    for i, m in enumerate(all_models):
        accuracy = round(m.accuracy * 100, 5)
        results = [i + 1, accuracy, m.features, m.alg, m.reg, m.cv]
        print(" | ".join('{0:{width}}'.format(str(r), width=max_len) for r in results))

Ultimately, it looks like model 6, 7 and 9 are the best models. They had the best accuracies, the best AUC scores, and they had the best sensitivity and specificity.

However, Model 9's sensitivity and specificity are more balanced (albeit mildly) than Model 6, and - even though Model 7's raw accuracy score is slightly better than Model 9 - Model 9 leverages cross validation so it should theoretically be more accurate on a broader range of unknown data than model 7. In fact, it is possible that Model 7's slightly better accuracy score could simply be because of how the data was split during training and testing.

So, I will be picking Model 9 as the best model.

def preprocess(test: pd.DataFrame):
    """ Preprocesses the dataset so that it can be used by Model 7 """
    X = df.loc[:, features]
    y = np.array(df.iloc[:,0])
    lda = LinearDiscriminantAnalysis().fit(X, y)
    cols = test.loc[:, features]
    return lda.transform(cols)
